Comparing Two Cities

This post compares police reports from the Summer of 2014 in both San Francisco and Seattle. The data is from from the https://data.seattle.gov and https://datasf.org/opendata/ sites.

Data Overview

Incident codes differ somewhat between the two cities. Thus in order to compare the two data sets, this report uses a combination of the indencent categories from the two cities incident categories from the two data sets mapped to the common set by matching key words from the Offense Type and Summarized Offense Description variables in the Seattle data and the Category and Descript variables in the San Francisco data.

The original Seattle data set contains over 1,000 incidents that were reported after August 31, 2014. These plus all non-criminal incidents from both cities are removed from the data sets. All other incidents are preserved albeit reclassified in some cases to the unified categories.

For spatial analysis, this report uses the reported longitude and latitude for each incident (the Longitude and Latitude Seattle variables and the X and Y San Francisco variables).

sfs <- sf %>%
  select(
    Category,
    Descript,
    Date,
    Time,
    PdDistrict,
    X,
    Y,
    Address
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    Time = paste(Time, ":00", sep = ""),
    Date = mdy_hms(paste(Date, Time, sep = " "), tz = "PST8PDT")
  ) %>%
  rename(
    offense_type = Category,
    description = Descript,
    date = Date,
    district = PdDistrict,
    lon = X,
    lat = Y,
    block = Address
  ) %>%
  select(
    -Time
  )

sfs$city <- rep("San Francisco", nrow(sfs))

seattles <- seattle %>%
  select(
    `Offense Type`,
    `Summarized Offense Description`,
    `Date Reported`,
    `District/Sector`,
    Longitude,
    Latitude,
    `Hundred Block Location`
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    `Date Reported` = mdy_hms(`Date Reported`, tz = "PST8PDT")
  ) %>%
  rename(
    description = `Offense Type`,
    offense_type = `Summarized Offense Description`,
    date = `Date Reported`,
    district = `District/Sector`,
    lon = Longitude,
    lat = Latitude,
    block = `Hundred Block Location`
  )

seattles$city <- rep("Seattle", nrow(seattles))

People Mostly Steal Stuff

The following charts show the top level crime categories that comprise 90% of the incident reports for San Francisco and Seattle between June 1, 2014 and August 31, 2014.

sf_clean <- sfsea %>%
  filter(
    city == "San Francisco"
  )

sf_levels <- sf_clean %>%
  group_by(
    category
  ) %>%
  summarize(
    count = n()
  ) %>%
  ungroup %>%
  arrange(
    desc(count)
  )

sf_levels$total <- rep(sum(sf_levels$count), nrow(sf_levels))
sf_levels %<>%
  mutate(
    share = count/total,
    cumshare = cumsum(share)
  )

sf_levels90 <- sf_levels %>%
  filter(
    cumshare <= 0.9
  ) %>%
  arrange(
    count
  )

sf_clean90 <- sf_clean[which(sf_clean$category %in% sf_levels90$category), ]
sf_clean90$category <- factor(sf_clean90$category, levels = sf_levels90$category)

sf90.plot <- sf_clean90 %>%
  ggplot(
    aes(category)
  ) +
  geom_bar(
    fill = "#F8766D", position = "dodge"
  ) +
  coord_flip() +
  labs( y = "Incident Count", x = "Crime Category", title = "Most Common Crimes \n (90% of San Fransisco \n Criminal Incident Reports)") +
  ylim(c(0, 10500))

sea_clean90 <- sea_clean[which(sea_clean$category %in% sea_levels90$category), ]

  ggplot(

  ) +

Although Seattleâ€™s population is only 78% the size of San Franciscoâ€™s population, Seattle police filed 18% more criminal incidents over the same period.

There are some interesting differences between the most common crimes in each of the two cities. In Seattle theft is by far the most common crime: vehicles mostly (cars, trucks, boats â€“ interestingly bikes have their own category). Seattle-ites also like to be rowdy, property damange and disorderly conduct make the top five.

Both cities unfortunately see a lot of assault (2nd highest category for San Francisco and 3rd highest for Seattle) and both cities see a fair amount of fraud and warrant arrests, but San Francisco seems to have a larger drug problem (or at least more drug arrests) as that category is 4th on the San Francisco list and is not even in the top eight for Seattle.

# per capita
top90_cat <- c(sea_levels90$category, sf_levels90$category)

top90 <- sfsea[which(sfsea$category %in% top90_cat), ]

top90_levels <- top90 %>%
  group_by(
    city,
    category
  ) %>%
  summarize(
    count = n()
  ) %>%
  ungroup %>%
  group_by(
    category
  ) %>%
  filter(
    count == max(count)  # want to arrange the categories in decending order by the max
  ) %>%                  # of the larger city count, not by the total count of both cities.
  ungroup %>%
  arrange(
    count
  )

pop <- data.frame(city = c("San Francisco", "Seattle"), pop = c(852469, 668324))

top90_levels %<>%
  left_join(., pop, by = "city") %>%
  mutate(
    per_capita = count / pop
  ) %>%
  arrange(
    per_capita
  )

top90_sum <- top90 %>%
  group_by(
    city,
    category
  ) %>%
  summarize(
    count = n(),
    pop = mean(pop)
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    per_1000_capita = 1000 * count / pop
  ) %>%
  ungroup

top90_sum$category <- factor(top90_sum$category, levels = top90_levels$category)

both.plot <- top90_sum %>%
  ggplot(
    aes(category, per_1000_capita)
  ) +
  geom_bar(
    aes(fill = city), position = "dodge", stat = "Identity"
  ) +
  coord_flip() +
  labs( y = "Incident Count per 1000 capita", x = "Crime Category", title = "Most Common Crimes \n in San Francisco and Seattle")

When looked at per-capita, the two cities show some significant differences and a few anomolies.

First, Seattle has more theft of all kinds than does San Francisco (over 5x the vehicle theft). Seattle also has more assaults and robberies per head over the time period. San Francisco, however, has more warrant arrests per capita than Seattle.

Interesting, the San Francisco data does not include any property damage reports. There are vandalism reports but the descriptions refer to proximity to highways, while the Seattle reports clearly include residential incidents. Perhaps more intesting in the case of missing persons, Seattle does not seem to have anyone reported missing over the Summer of 2014, whereas San Francisco has quite a few. San Franciscans also appear to be more suspicious than those in Seattle as Seattle reports no suspicious occurances.

Crime Sleeps In

  ylim(c(-2, 3))

Looking at incidents by time of day shows that contrary to common belief, the dead of night is not when most crimes occur. In fact, in both San Francisco and Seattle crime does not pick up until after 9 am, peaking in the afternoon/early evening, and then usually calls it a night by 10 or 11 pm.

Notable deviations from normal schedule for San Francisco include a mid-day spike in robbery and a steady rise in traffic violations throughout the workday and into the late evening. Seattle is more true to form, although disorderly conduct does continue well into the night.

Crime is Highest in Poorest, Most Visited by Tourists, and Most Densely Populated Parts of Town

Plotting each incidentâ€™s location shows consentrations in the densest (and lower income) parts of the city. (Grey areas in the maps below indicate county boundaries which may extent over water.)

San Francisco data shows the highest consentration of crime in the low-income Tenderloin and Mission St.Â corredor along with the high density North Beach neighborhood. Theft (bringt pink) is also consentrated in the tourist areas (Market St.Â corredor and along the warves).

Seattle sees the most crime in the Downtown and University District.

Conclusion

Differences in incident categories and police prorities explain some of the differences between the reported crime levels in San Francisco and Seattle. However, there still remain differences in the types of crimes most common in each city. But even with the differences in focus by criminals, the levels of crime through the day are similar and are concentrated in the poorer and more dense parts of each city.
